description:
Hiking with my partner ahead of me something rustled in the dirt on the uphill side of the trail.  It stopped right beside me - about 5 feet away up the sandy hill - and I thought it was a snake. Then I noticed it was too short for a snake and a bit thicker in diameter from tip to tail.  I realized that could only mean one thing - a salamander.  I said it out loud as the realization hit, "Holy sh*t! It's a salamander!" And even though I was hiking with my camera in my hand the sucker took off faster than I could lift the camera to take a shot.  It raced behind a stump and then under a large rock outcropping.  

I'd say it was 8-10 inches long and was flash of sand colour (probably because of the sand being flung), green and brown.  Man, it was fast!  I think it was sleeping on the cliff/bank and my partner walking ahead woke it up and then I startled it by blurting out my expletive with excitement.  

I can't be sure of the exact identification but this was the closest I could find for the area, size and colouring.  Not sure if anyone else has any notes about Pacific Giant Salamanders in this area as I've read that above-ground sightings are rare.  Sorry there are no photos - and good luck to anyone trying to photograph that!  A silent drone, or drone w/ a very good telephoto is gonna be the only way to catch those critters unawares.
place_guess: Fraser Valley, BC, Canada

description:
Saw this spider on the same hike as the salamander.  

It has a shiny abdomen so the suggested species of Ant-mimic doesn't really align with that feature.  I'm not sure what to classify this as but I thought it was interesting.
